While I understand short staffing can occur unexpectedly and cause difficulties, that also is a time when you can step up your game on customer service and be creative in keeping the customers happy.  When we arrived, we were not informed that service was running very slow, a fact we learned from fellow customers, some of them as they walked out the door after waiting in excess of one hour for food that never came.  After waiting an hour ourselves, we told the waitress that we needed to get back to work and could we get our food to go.  Not only did we never see the waitress again, but we had to leave the restaurant to go back to work without any food at all.  Customer service can make or break a restaurant, regardless of the quality of food.  Someone could have informed us so we could make a decision on whether we waited or not; someone could have offered something to tide us over during the wait (fruit, a piece of toast, anything?); someone could have offered a discount for the inconvenience or perhaps a coupon for a future visit; someone could have and should have, but they did not.  Customer service is important - a fact that obviously should be revisited.
